    <h1>The Bahá’í Calendar</h1>
    <blockquote>
      <p>“… yet another historic step in the manifestation of the unity of the people of Bahá and the unfoldment of Bahá’u’lláh’s World Order.”</p>
    </blockquote>

    <h2>What is happening?</h2>
    <blockquote>
      <p>We call upon the Bahá’ís of the East and West to adopt, on that auspicious occasion [20 March 2015], the provisions that will unite them in the common implementation of the Badí‘ calendar.</p>
      <footer>- <em>Universal House of Justice, 10 July 2014</em></footer>
    </blockquote>

    <h2>A new calendar</h2>
    <blockquote>
      <p>The Báb signalized the importance of the dispensation which He came to herald by inaugurating a new calendar. In this, as in the Gregorian Calendar, the lunar month is abandoned and the solar year is adopted.</p>
      <footer>- <em>Dr. J. E. Esslemont, Bahá’u’lláh and the New Era</em></footer>
    </blockquote>

    <h2>A common calendar</h2>
    <blockquote>
      <p>In the not distant future it will be necessary that all peoples in the world agree on a common calendar.</p>
      <p>It seems, therefore, fitting that the new age of unity should have a new calendar free from the objections and associations which make each of the older calendars unacceptable to large section of the world’s population, and it is difficult to see how any other arrangement could exceed in simplicity and convenience that proposed by the Báb.</p>
      <footer>- <em>Dr. J. E. Esslemont, Bahá’u’lláh and the New Era</em></footer>
    </blockquote>

    <h2>Badí‘ Calendar background</h2>
    <blockquote>
      <p>The Báb introduced a new calendar, known now as the Badí‘ or Bahá'í calendar. According to this calendar, a day is the period from sunset to sunset. In the Bayán, the Báb ordained the month of ‘Alá' to be the month of fasting, decreed that the day of Naw-Rúz should mark the termination of that period, and designated Naw-Rúz as the Day of God. Bahá'u'lláh confirms the Badí‘ calendar wherein Naw-Rúz is designated as a feast.</p>
      <p>Naw-Rúz is the first day of the new year. It coincides with the spring equinox in the northern hemisphere, which usually occurs on 21 March. Bahá'u'lláh explains that this feast day is to be celebrated on whatever day the sun passes into the constellation of Aries (i.e. the vernal equinox), even should this occur one minute before sunset. Hence Naw-Rúz could fall on 20, 21, or 22 March, depending on the time of the equinox.</p>
      <footer>- <em>Kitáb-i-Aqdas, n26</em></footer>
    </blockquote>

    <h2>Badí‘ Calendar basics</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Badí‘ = “wondrous”</li>
      <li>The Bahá’í year consists of 19 months of 19 days each (361 days total)</li>
      <ul>
        <li>4-5 intercalary days (Ayyám-i-Há) between the 18th and 19th month</li>
      </ul>
      <li>Each month and day is named after the attributes of God</li>
      <ul>
        <li>The Báb named them according to the verses of the “Prayer of Glory” – an Islamic prayer</li>
      </ul>
      <li>The first day of the week is Saturday</li>
      <ul>
        <li>Friday is the day of rest</li>
      </ul>
      <li>Year 1 is fixed to the year of the Declaration of the Báb (23 May 1844)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Badí‘ Calendar units</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>19 days = 1 month</li>
      <li>19 months + Ayyám-i-Há = 1 year</li>
      <li>19 years = 1 Vahíd (“unity”)</li>
      <li>19 Vahíds = 1 Kull-i-Shay’ (“all things”)</li>
    </ul>

