    <h2>What about the previous guidance?</h2>
    <blockquote>
      <p>Unless specifically abrogated by these new provisions, previous guidance and clarifications pertaining to the calendar and the observance of the Nineteen Day Feast and Holy Days remain binding, such as</p>
      <ul>
        <li>the beginning of the day at sunset,</li>
        <li>the suspension of work,</li>
        <li>and the hours at which certain Holy Days are commemorated.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>In future, a change in circumstances may well require additional measures.</p>
      <footer>- <em>Universal House of Justice, 10 July 2014</em></footer>
    </blockquote>

    <h2>How do we call dates?</h2>
    <blockquote>
      <p>The House of Justice has made no decision regarding the dating of correspondence and documents, and Bahá’í institutions and individual believers are free to use their discretion in this regard.</p>
      <footer>- <em>Department of the Secretariat, 10 July 2014</em></footer>
    </blockquote>

    <h2>The power of Divine Revelation</h2>
    <blockquote>
      <p>The adoption of a new calendar in each dispensation is a symbol of the power of Divine Revelation to reshape human perception of material, social, and spiritual reality. Through it, sacred moments are distinguished, humanity's place in time and space reimagined, and the rhythm of life recast. Next Naw-Rúz will mark yet another historic step in the manifestation of the unity of the people of Bahá and the unfoldment of Bahá’u’lláh’s World Order.</p>
      <footer>- <em>Universal House of Justice, 10 July 2014</em></footer>
    </blockquote>

